│ is working in the wrong direction. The transformation `select Cond, TrueVal, false` -> `and Cond, TrueVal` is only safe if `TrueVal` being poison implies that `Cond` is also poison (so  │
│ the AND would be poison anyway). But what we actually need to check is whether `Cond` being non-poison guarantees that `TrueVal` is non-poison.\n\nHowever, given the complexity and the  │
│ fact that `icmp samesign` instructions have special poison semantics, the safest fix is to disable this optimization when dealing with `icmp samesign` instructions.\n\nBut wait - let me │
│ reconsider. The actual problem is more fundamental. The `impliesPoison(TrueVal, CondVal)` check is supposed to verify that if `TrueVal` is poison, then `CondVal` must also be poison.    │
│ This would make the transformation safe because in the original select, if `CondVal` is poison, the result is undefined anyway, and in the AND, if `CondVal` is poison, the result is     │
│ poison.\n\nHowever, in our case, `TrueVal` can be poison while `CondVal` is not poison (false but not poison). This means `impliesPoison(TrueVal, CondVal)` should return false, but it's │
│ returning true.\n\nLooking at the `impliesPoison` implementation, it seems the issue might be that `icmp` instructions are considered to not create poison (`canCreatePoison` returns     │
│ false for `ICmp`), so the analysis falls back to checking the operands. But `icmp samesign` can create poison based on the sign comparison, which isn't captured by the operand           │
│ analysis.\n\nGiven this complexity, the most practical fix is to add a specific check for `icmp samesign` instructions and avoid the transformation in such cases.\n\nHowever, after      │
│ further analysis, I realize that the real issue is in the `impliesPoison` function itself - it doesn't properly handle `icmp samesign` instructions. But since fixing `impliesPoison`     │
│ might be complex and have wider implications, the safer approach is to modify the select folding logic to be more conservative with icmp instructions that can produce                    │
│ poison.\n\nActually, looking at the LLVM language reference, `icmp samesign` produces poison when the operands are not of the same sign. This poison production is independent of other   │
│ icmp operations, so `impliesPoison` cannot reliably determine the relationship.\n\nThe correct fix is to add a check that prevents this transformation when `TrueVal` is an `icmp`        │
│ instruction with the `samesign` flag, because such instructions can be poison independently of the condition."})                                                                          │
